The door latch mechanism on the 3D40 is particularly prone to breaking when opening the filament door due to lack of support for the forces pushing against the latch when it breaks loose and slams backward into the edge of its socket. This latch is designed with a long support intended to mitigate that weakness.

This is the first design I came up with that didn't break loose in testing. If you use this and it fails, I'd love to see some photos or a description of the failure so I can further improve the design!

I recommend printing this item with 100% infill for strength. I also suggest using a raft, as this item prints on its backside, which needs to be a smooth surface to adhere well when glued to the previous support of the broken part on the door itself.

Notes:

  • currently working on a version with supports on both sides for cases where the entire support may have broken off the door when the original latch did.

Printer:

Dremel IdeaBuilder 3D40

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Infill:

100%

Attachment

I recommend using superglue to attach the part where the previous part used to be. You may need to adjust the fit by trimming or sanding the end of the notch to reduce friction when it engages with the ridge on the printer door receiver socket.
Designed in Tinkercad using basic shapes and one hole to make the notch.

title: Kraken Mare Xplorer
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is a "near-scale" model of a proposed NASA robotic submarine that will be used for exploring the liquid ethane/methane lakes of Saturn's largest moon, Titan. It is a "near-scale" model due to the lack of detailed, measured drawings for this vessel--I only had two drawings for reference.

Titan is Saturn's largest moon and it is the second largest moon in our solar system. Titan was discovered in 1655 by Christian Huygens. The NASA Cassini-Huygens orbiter/probe entered Titan orbit in 2004 with the Huygens descent probe landing on Titan in January 2005. Titan has a methane cycle similar to Earth's water cycle. Lakes exist at high northern latitudes. Lakes and larger seas or mare are filled with liquid ethane and methane. An average, estimated (actual depth is unknown) depth of 20 m for these mare would be equivalent to twice the volume of Earth's oil and gas reserves.

The proposed submarine was designed by Ralph Lorenz for NASA Institute for Advanced Concepts (NIAC). There are three bodies of liquid ethane that are targeted for exploration: Kraken-1, Kraken-2, and Ligeia Mare. The large dorsal fin on the explorer is an X-Band Phased Array Antenna. Similarly, the discs on either side of the main mast fin are X-Band Omni Antenna.

This model was intentionally designed with numerous holes, channels, and ducts for enabling the vessel to completely submerge in a body of water (e.g., pool, bathtub, bucket, etc.). If you are interested in experimenting with the diving/surfacing abilities of this model, you can tape an Alka-Seltzer tablet inside the nose section. Carefully, poke a couple of small holes in the tape, thread the cap onto the Karken Mare Xplorer, and place the model in some water. As the vessel submerges, the water will activate the tablet and cause an explosion of gas to fill the interior of the ship enabling it to surface. This is an experimental feature of this model and it might not perform to your expectations. Good luck and have fun!

Tip: Use Testors Cement for Plastic Models No. 3512 for assembly. If you can't locate this product locally, consider ordering from: squadron.com.

References

"How I Came to Design Extraterrestrial Robot Submarines: Part 1 - Probing Saturn's Moon, Titan," Ralph Lorenz; SERVO Magazine, May 2015, pgs. 43 - 47.

"How I Came to Design Extraterrestrial Robot Submarines: Part 2 - Sailing Ligeia, Diving Kraken," Ralph Lorenz; SERVO Magazine, June 2015, pgs. 38 - 44.

"Titan Submarine : Vehicle Design and Operations Concept for the Exploration of the Hydrocarbon Seas of Saturn's Giant Moon," Ralph D. Lorenz, et.al., 46th Lunar and Planetary Science Conference (2015)

Designed it in 1-2 hours, so please be gentle on the design its far from perfect.

You can attach it with 2 "Tesa Powerstrips Large" or normal double sided Tape to your wall.

Just printed one. It's much better. Because the top is angled, the rafting part looks a little cheesy but it can be sanded down or acetone vapor polished. Now I don't remember what version I printed. lol. There are 3 minor things:
1) The bottom plate has stands which is a great idea! however, the stands aren't high enough yet to let the bottom of the kk2 sit properly because of the solder on the pins. I would humbly suggest increasing the height by1-1.5mm just to be safe.
2) the 4 hole pattern is off by just enough that when the bolts go through the top plate, they tend to angle which makes it hard to line up the bottom plate. I re-drilled with a 3mm bit but I would increase the holes somehow around the frame to 3.5mm somehow to allow for some deviation in these boards. it's tricky though because your walls are real close as it is to the holes.
3) both the motor and receiver connection holes need to be lengthened at the top by I'm guessing 2mm to allow the top connectors to fit in. as it is now, the top edges of the holes are directly over top of the uppermost pins.
You almost have the perfect KK2 housing! you may want to increase the depth of the logo a small bit as that surface lies directly on the table an squashes the lovely graphics.

description.text:
The MMID Foundation, in co-operation with Red Lobster Divers, has developed ‘The Lobster’. A SCUBA product that will simplify the interaction between the buddy and divers with a physical disability. The Lobster makes diving safer and more fun for both the diver and buddy. The system is designed for divers with a physical disability, however it might prove to be usefull for anyone who is willing to use it.

The system has three main features:

  • The firm grip of the bar allows the buddy to orientate himself and the diver underwater.
  • The system will improve stability of the diver, this allowed one of the divers with a muscular disease to dive without the physical guidance of a buddy for the fist time in her life!
  • The floating strap around the inflator hose will make it float, making it easier to reach and operate for the buddy.

MMID Foundation
MMID Foundation is initiated by the employees of MMID, an international oriented product development agency, based in Delft, the Netherlands and Essen and Ulm in Germany.

Sharing is a central factor in MMID’s philosophy. Sharing knowledge and taking care of each other: sharing and caring. From this thought, and social involvement, the employees of MMID decided to found the MMID Foundation.

With this Foundation the MMID team would like to share valuable products and knowledge with those who are not able to access it in any other way.

Red Lobster Divers
Red Lobster Divers is a foundation that promotes and enables the possibility to snorkel and scuba dive for people who normally have difficulties in joining regular dive clubs or dive schools. Especially for people with mental or physical disabilities , but also ASS, are welcome to participate. The foundation has special training programs for both candidate divers as well as dive guides.

The Red Lobster Divers organises scuba training in various places in Holland and organises diving holidays to e.g. Bonaire.

This is a Solidworks created feature. It consists of many different parts that come together to form Cinderella's Pumpkin Carriage. This is a day calendar with rotating discs inserted into the pumpkin that tell the month and day of the month. There is also a index or business card holder in the shape of a little chair that attaches to the pumpkin. The back of this chair also features the iconic Cinderella glass slipper. The top of the pumpkin also comes off to allow for easy insertion of the discs that tell the month and day of the month. Holding the wheels of the pumpkin are swirls. These swirls when the wheels are attached create a cool sunburst effect with the cut-outs in the wheels. The wheels also feature a small crown to go with the Cinderella theme. The discs and pumpkin bottom feature a hole that is a little more than 3/16 of an inch wide. Into this can be inserted a dowel or skewer of 3/16 inch diameter. This acts as a mechanism for the discs to rotate upon and to keep them in the pumpkin itself. The pumpkin itself rests in a base that cradles it in a way to allow for the pumpkin to be taken out if need be. This base also has small butterflies between the areas where the swirls are inserted. The stem, in addition, is inserted into the top of the pumpkin top to give it more of a pumpkin effect.
